			<blockquote><i>This should help keep it from being a way to park a mob and nuke it till dead.</i></blockquote>Very good point ... it would have to be some kind of taunt where it just moves up a tad somehow? I don't know how aggro works.<br><br>It would have to be so that you couldn't nuke it from a mile away la-dee-da no risk ... but just so that maybe you could peel it off the cleric et al.<br><br>The motivation being the over-pull and how folks speak of "pet mez" ... <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0><br><br>Thanks for the feedback ( as if I'm a game designer ) about this suggestion.<br><br>When it occured to me I thought it'd be nice because conceivably a little quick ( "tough" ) distraction pet could be the mage's version ( at level 16 say ) of wizzies' evac'ing / stunning or enchanters' stunning / mezzing or necros mezzing / feigning.<br><br>And then multiple "distractions" could be similar to the AoE versions of spells other folk get. And it'd add some utility for groups / raids, without breaking the mold of the class.<br><br><img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0><br><br>EDITED: Adding part about enchanters <blockquote><i>This spell essentially allows mages to CC unmezable mobs.</i></blockquote>Well, the spell's not in game ... <b><i>but you could have the "taunt" be a proc, with mob level limits or some save? </b></i><br><br>So the level 16 pet's "distraction" proc / spell would just have a level limitation ... like enchanter's mezzes?<br><br>I don't think if that was added it'd step on enchanter toes ... make a lame pet for CC and then the mage can't do lots of DPS ( <b><i>assuming it's not a stackable pet ... like Eye of Zomm?</b></i>)<br><br> ... so if no enchanter is around ( who can CC while having pets and cast clarities, stuns, roots ... which are spells mages lack completely ) and no bard around ( who can CC while having pets and sing clarities ) maybe the mage could do some ghetto control?<br><br><b><i>Oh, okay, have the pet be limited in duration?</b></i><br><br>That could address both of the above? <br><br><b><i>Perhaps the mage inherits the hate generated by the aforementioned pet once it disappears?</b></i><br><br>Thanks again for pointing out errors / potential exploits ... this is what devs need, I would think?<p>Message Edited by inoffensive_name on <span class=date_text>06-03-2004</span> <span class=time_text>01:34 PM</span>
